.TH htons 3
.SH NAME
.PP
\*Lhtons\*O - Converts an unsigned short (16-bit) integer from host-byte order to a 2-byte Internet network integer
.SH LIBRARY
.PP
Standard C Library (\*Llibc.a\*O)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.sS
\*Lunsigned short htons\*O (\*L
.nL
	\*Lunsigned short \*Vhostshort\*L) ;
.sE
.SH PARAMETERS
.PP
...\"from TP "
.VL
.LI "\*Vhostshort"
\*OSpecifies a 16-bit integer in host-byte order.
.LE
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
.iX "htons function"
.iX "host-byte order" "converting short integer"
.iX "network-byte order" "converting short integer"
.iX "short integer" "converting to network-byte order"
The \*Lhtons(\|)\*O (host-to-network short) function
converts an unsigned short (16-bit) integer from host-byte order to
Internet network-byte order.
.P
\*OThe Internet network requires address and port reference data
in network-byte order (most significant byte leftmost, least significant
byte rightmost). Use the \*Lhtons(\|)\*O function to convert
address and port short integers from host-byte order to Internet
network-byte order.
.\" Commented out per Mary Walker -- QAR 13674
.\".P 
.\"The \*Lhtonl(\|)\*O function is defined as a \*Vbig-endian\*O macro in the
.\"\*Lnetinet/in.h\*O header file for machine environments where network-byte
.\"order and host-byte order are identical.
.SH RETURN VALUES
.PP
\*OUpon successful completion, the \*Lhtons(\|)\*O function
returns a 16-bit short integer in Internet
network-byte order.
.SH RELATED INFORMATION
.PP
Functions:
\*Lhtonl\*O(3),
\*Lntohl\*O(3),
\*Lntohs\*O(3)
